{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_groomcreek_ver04/data/sn96060774/00414218258/1930103101/0114.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nflogales International\nDevoted to the interests ot Nogales and Vicinity\nPUBLISHED EVERY TUESDAY AND FRIDAY MOENi.NO\nAt 225 Grand Ave., Nogales, Arizona\nCRAIG POTTINGER Owner and Publisher\nRALPH RAWSTHORNE Business Manager\nAL KIRK Managing Editor\nSubscription Rate S4.QU A Year 52.50 Six Months, 45 cents a\nMonth.\nINTERNATIONAL PLATFORM\nBetter Drainage To Make Floods Impossible More Conventions\nMore Tourists\nA Law To Prohibit Jaywalking A Greater Nogales\nA Motorcycle Road Patrol To Regulate Traffic On the Nogales-\nTucson Road Development Os Mining And Agricultural Re\nsources Os This District.\nEntered as second class matter February 3, 1928 at the\npostoffice at Nogales, Arizona, under the Act of March 3. 1979.\nDEMOCRATIC TICKET\nCONGRESSIONAL\n.Congressman L. W. DOUGLAS\nSTATE\nGovernor GEO. W. P. HUNT\nSupreme Judge A. C. LOCKWOOD\nSecretary of State SCOTT WHITE\nAttorney-General K. BERRY PETERSON\nState Auditor ANA FROHMILLER\nState Treasurer MIT SIMMS\nSupt. Public Instruction C. 0. CASE\nCorporation Commissioner CHARLES R. HOWE\nState Mine Inspector TOM FOSTER\nCOUNTY\nJudge of Superior Court W. A. O\u2019CONNOR\nClerk of Superior Court ROBERT E. LEE\nState Senator C. C. CRENSHAW\nState Representative E. F. BOHLINGER\nSheriff VICTOR J. WAGER\nSupervisor, Dist. No. 1 S. C. <|UNG\nSupervisor, Dist. No. 2 JAMES A. HARRISON\nSupervisor, Dist. No. 3 W. T. ROATH\nTreasurer A. DUMBAULD\nRecorder LUCY MITCHELL\nCounty Attorney E. R. THURMAN\nAssessor HARRY V. FARRIOR\nCounty School Supt LULA R. LARIMORE\nPRECINCT\nJustice of Peace, Pet. No. 1 CHARLES E. HARDY\nJustice of Peace, Pet. No. 2 G. J. BIBLE\nJustice of Peace, Pet. No. 3 DANIEL H. CARGILL\nConstable of Pet. No. 1 W. S. (Dad) LARCOM\nConstable of Pet. No. 2 JAMES G. KANE\nConstable of Pet. No. 3 FRED PYEATT\nLet\u2019s Stop That Republican Favoritism\n9\nIn view of the disclosures made by the Nogales\nInternational with reference to the tax reductions\nmade by the republican board of supervisors, sitting\nas a board of equalization, we hope that the taxpay\ners of Santa Cruz county, regardless of party affilia\ntion, will see to it that such a thing is impossible dur\ning the next two years.\nThere is but one way to do this.\nCAST YOUR BALLOT FOR DEMOCRATIC\nSUPERVISORS at the November election and BE\nASSURED OF A SQUARE DEAL when it again\ncomes time to value and tax your property.\nThe very nerve of the republican supervisors to 1\nutterly disregard public opinion and go right ahead!\ncutting and slashing property values\u2014when the pro\nperty belongs to relatives or republican leaders\u2014\nreally their audacity has no equal in the annals of\nlocal polities.\nSurely the fair-minded people of Santa Cruz!\ncounty have had enough of this sort of thing. It is!\ntime to call a halt to the practice of such favoritism\nand the juggling of the county\u2019s tax rolls to gratify\nthe wishes and reduce the tax obligations of republi-!\ncans who may have political power.\nSecond only to the nerve of the republican super-1\nvisors themselves is the nerve of the republican i\nmouthpiece which recently printed a statement to the I\neffect that the supervisors merely used the valuation\nfigures furnished by Harry Farrior, the democratic\ncounty assessor.\nEvery man who knows anything about the tax\nlaw at all knows that this was impossible. The pro-j\nperty was assessed by the State Tax Survey Board;\n.and the asesssor was compelled by law to insert in the\ntax rolls the values given him by that Board.\nThe tell-tale green ink that was used by the re-i\npublican supervisors in writing in the reduced valua\ntions stands as an undeniable indictment of their act.\nThe republican mouthpiece would have the tax\npayers believe, however, that the reductions were\nmade in the interest of economy. If that is true, why\nwere not all property valuations reduced in the same\nproportion as those on the property of E. K. Gum\nming and H. R. Sisk?\nThere are almost three democrats to every re-\npublican in Santa Cruz county, as shown by the regis\ntration.\nRepublican extravagance and partiality will be a\nthing of the past if the democrats will stick together.\nWe can fairly snow those republicans under if we will\nall vote right next Tuesday.\nO--o\u2014-0-\nThe Truth About The Tax Rate\nThe local Republican mouthpiece continues its\ncampaign of misrepresentation and is grasping at ev\nery straw possible in a losing effort to re-elect the\nthree Republican supervisors.\nThe G. 0. P. organ in its Wednesday\u2019s issue again\ncarried an editorial giving entire credit for the reduc\ned tax rate this year to the Republican Board of Su\npervisors.\nTHE REPUBLICAN SUPERVISORS\u2014FRED\nHANNAH, MALCOLM MIDDLETON ANND A. S.\nHENDERSON\u2014KNOW THEMSELVES THAT\nTHE REPUBLICAN MOUTHPIECE IS WRONG\nIN GIVING THEM THE CREDIT. They know it\ni, firmly yet we haven\u2019t seen them reprimand that news\npaper for misrepresenting facts to the voters.\nWe repeat what we have said before that the en\ntire credit for the lower tax rate is due to the great\namount of back taxes collected by the Democratic\ncounty treasurer under House Bill No. 127 and reduc\ntion in the Nogales school tax rate and that the Re\npublican supervisors are no more entitled to that cre\ndit than is a two year old child. The supervisors can\nneither lower nor raise the school rate.\nWe recall that more than a year ago when there\nwas an increase in the Nogales school tax rate the\nRepublican organ came out with big headlines and\nannounced the fact, hoping at that time to bring cen\nsure on the school superintendent. They played up\nthat raise in big type but they didn\u2019t play up the fact\nj this year that the Nogales school rate was materally\nreduced.\n_ The reduced Nogales school rate contributed to\nj 50 percent of the total reduction in the tax rate to be\n1 1 paid by Nogales citizens this year. The SCHOOL SU\nPERINTENDENT AND THE SCHOOL BOARD\nARE GETTING NO CREDIT FROM THE REPUB\nLICAN ORGAN. In their opinion the Republican su\npervisors are entitled to all the credit.\nVoters of Nogales and Santa Cruz County are\nij too intelligent a group of folks to be misled by the Re\n!jpublican organ. They know where credit is due for\nlithe lower tax rate and THEY KNOW THAT SU\nPERVISORS HANNAH, MIDDLETON AND\nj!HENDERSON ARE NOT ENTITLED TO ONE\nj OUNCE OF THAT CREDIT.\n\u2014o\u2014o\u2014o\u2014\nMilk Fund Growing\nIn no case where a public emergenney exists\u2014\nwhere worthy charitable work is needed \u2014have the\n\u2022Elks ever been found wanting. In fact the B. P. 0. E.\njareusually in the front rank in coming to the aid of\ntheir fellow men. Their name, Benevolent Protec\ntive Order of Elks, could not have been better chosen\nfor the order is certainly a benevolent and protective\norganization in the true sense of the term.\nIn responding to the appeal of the Nogales Inter-\nI national for money to furnish milk to poor and under\nnourished children in our public schools, the Elks\nLodge of Nogales came through handsomely, contri\nbuting $25.00 at their meeting Tuesday night.\nThis showed a very splendid spirit, but is not un\nusual for this fraternal order.\nAnother contribution that was especially appre\nciated was one from a prominent business man who\ngave SIO.OO to the cause but who requested that his\nname not be mentioned. He preferred to just say that\nit was \u201ccontributed by a friend.\u201d\nThe Nogales Lions Club deserves much credit for J\nithe enthusiastic interest they are taking in the move\njment. They have placed milk bottles in many pro\njminent places down town and each week they go a\nround and collect the public contributions.\nThe milk fund is gradually growing and we feel\nconfident before this campaign ends sufficient money\nj will have been contributed to supply the much-needed\nmilk for poor school children whose parents are un\nable do pay 20 cents a week in order to supply this\nnourishing food.\nContributions may be made at any time direct to\nI the Nogales International or to any member of the\ni Lions Club, and the convenient bottles are always on\nhand to receive spare change.\n\u2014o\u2014o\u2014o\u2014\nls Well Qualified\nS. C. Jung, Democratic candidate for Supervisor\n|of District No. 1, has been a resident of Nogales for\nthe past 15 years. He came to Nogales to accept a po-\nsition with Albert Steinfeld Co., wholesale grocery\nj department leaving their employ in 1920 to accept a j\nposition with the Nogales National Bank where he\nI served for nine years as assistant cashier and director\nof that institution.\nIn May, 1919, Mr. Jung severed his connections\n[With the Nogales National Bank to engage in the gen\njcral insurance business which he has been conducting\nI since that time.\nSig. as he is generally known, served for two terms c\noil the Board of Aldermen of Nogales under Duane j\nj_>ii\u2019d, Mayor, one of the most efficient and economical |t\ni administrations that Nogales has ever had.\nMr. Jung is well qualified to serve the best inter- c\nests of the taxpayers of Nogales and Santa Cruz r\nCounty and when he is elected to the office of Super- i\nvisor of District No. 1 on November 4th the taxpay- v\n!ers can rest assured that they have chosen the proper\nNOGALES INTERNATIONAL\n-i candidate for that office.\nDistrict No. 1. in which Mr. Jung is a candidate,\nij comprises the west part of Nogales to Bank\u2019s Bridge,\nand Tubac, Amado and Ruby precincts. In the interest\nIjoi the county and its people he should be elected.\ntied C, C. Crenshaw To The Senate!\nIf the people of Santa Cruz County want to elect\n3 a capaole Senator to represent them in tile next legis\nt lature they should vote on November 4th for C. C.\nCrenshaw, the Democratic nominee.\nMr. Crenshaw has served the City of Nogales\nfaithfully and well for the past three years as a mem\nber of the Board of Aldermen. He* also served the\nCounty of Santa Cruz as it\u2019s Representative in the\nLegislature in the 7th session of that body and there\nbecame known as one of the leaders and one of the\nmost influential men in the House.\nI Mr. Crenshaw has stated to the editor of this pa\nll per that when he decided to announce his candidacy\nfor the senate he immediately resigned as a member\n\u2019j of the Board of Aldermen for the reason that he did\nnot want any employee of the city to feel that he had\nj to vote for him or refrain from expressing his opinion\n11 for fear of losing his position. To us this seems very\nj lair and Mr. Crenshaw should certainly be commended\nI for his attitude of fair play.\nj There seems to be no question but what Mr. Cren\n'j shaw will win by a large majority, the question is just\nI how large. Vote for him and help swell this majority.\no 0 o\u2014\nij\nBusiness Man Heads State Committee\nvVhen the Democrats of Arizona met at Phoenix\ni in September and named C. E. Addams as their state\nchairman they selected a real business man for that\njob.\nAddams has made a success of his duties from the\nvery day he took over the important post.\nThe first thing he did was to wipe out the deficit\nhanging over from the 1928 campaign. He sent letters\nj throughout the state to county committeemen asking\nif there were any unpaid 1928 bills in their respective\ncounties. Then he saw to it that those accounts were\npaid.\nAnd, furthermore, there will be no unpaid bills\nremaining at the close of the campaign ending next\nTuesday, because Addams has handled his post as\nstate chairman in a strictly business-like manner and\nj is seeing to it that all bills are paid.\nI Mr. Addams was the Hunt manager prior to the\nj primary. He did a good job in that capacity and he is\ndoing the same kind of a job toward bringing about a\nsweeping victory for the entire Democratic ticket at\nj Tuesday\u2019s election.\nI It well pays to have a business man at the head of\nthe state committee. The Democratic party is fortun\nate in having selected C. E. Addams.\nThree Good Reasons\nj!\n,i There are three good reasons why the Democratic\nticket should sweep Santa Cruz County Tuesday.\nU The business depression under the Republican\nregime\u2014nation, state and county\u2014has disgusted the\npublic in general to such an extent that they want a\ncomplete change.\n2. The registration in Santa Cruz County is al\nmost 3 to 1 Democratic. A total of 2232 persons can\nvote. Os this number. 1528 are registered as Demo\ncrats, 607 as Republicans and 97 as Non-Partisans. If\nthe Democrats stand by their ticket there will be a\nDemocratic landslide. j\n3. Santa Cruz County voters want a change in\nthe county administration. They have had enough of!\nthe extravagance of the Republican Board of Super\nvisors\u2014an extravagance entirely uncalled for, par\nticularly during a business depression when the strict-\nest kind of economy should have been practiced.\no o0\nBohlinger For Representative\nA Democratic nominee whose election Tuesday\nis a foregone conclusion is E. F. Bohlinger of Pata\ngonia, who seeks to represent Santa Cruz County in\nthe lower house of the state legislature.\n\u201cEd as he is better known to his host of friends\nthroughout the county, has been a resident of Santa\nCruz County 22 years and of Arizona 30 years, and\nduring that period has been actively engaged in min\ning and other pursuits. He is well qualified to serve\nthe people of this county in the legislature.\nMr. Bohlinger for years has been in charge of the\ninterests of the estate of the late Colonel Richardson\nof Patagonia. He is a trustee of the Nogales Elks\nLodge, prominent in business circles of the county,\npublic-spirited in all matters having for their goal\nthe betterment of conditions in this county, and in\nthe legislature he will make a valuable team mate to\nC. C. Crenshaw, the next state senator from this\ncounty.\n\nBuy In Nogales\nMuch has been said about patronizing home in- i\ndustries but we feel that the importance of the sub- 1\nject justifies again calling it to the attention of the t\ncitizens of Nogales. 1\nIn looking over the records of the county re- t\ncorder\u2019s office we find that many purchases have been\nmade by well known Nogales citizens in other cities, t\nnotably Tucson and while we have no crow to pick\nwith Tucson, we do feel that the people living in No- 11\n(Turn to Page Seven)\nNOGALES, ARIZ., FRIDAY. OCT. 31. 1930\nMovie Men Link\nHands With Caliente\nAGUA CALIENTE, Baja Calif\nornia. Mexico, Oct. 30\u2014Hollywood\nhas linked hands Stronger than ev\ner with Agua Caliente, as James N.\nCrofton, General Manager of the\nAgua Caliente Jockey Club, who has\ngone East to recruit prominent sta\nbles for the second annual Winter\nRace Meeting, that opens Xmas\nDay for an eighty one day session,\n5 a^so carries with him commissions\nfrom half a dozen prominent mem\nbers of the film colony to secure\nthem, if possible, high class and\nhigh priced thoroughbreds, in train\ni Ing, that will be fit and ready to\nS race when the first bugle call\nsounds. Also a millionaire realty\noperator in Los Angeles has asked\nCrofton to keep an eye open for\nhim for a blue blood equine that\nmight be able to capture the se\n-1 cond renewal of the $140,000 Agua\n1 Caliente Handicap, the \u201cWorld\u2019s\nj richest race\u201d, to be run March 22,\nT riexi,. As Crofton also races a\n\"string\u201d, himself, and would natur\n-1 ally not at all adverse to captur\ning the rich prize, he certainly has\nhis hands full.\nA1 Jolson, who recently acquired\nsome yearlings which Johnny Co\nburn bought for him at the Sara\ntoga sales, and the two year old,\nConcord, at private sale from the\nNewtondale Stable, is said to be one\nr of the film colony whom Crofton\nrepresents. Roual Walsh, famous\ndirector of the California cinema\nj colony who last season bought Grey\nola just before this fast daughter\nof \u00b0rsy Lag won the Agua Caliente\nDerby, is reported another, and\nBobby Crawford, also a noted dir\nector, still a third. Joe Toplipsky,\nwho entered the ownership ranks\na the recent Summer Meeting, by\npurchasing a \u201cstring\u201d from the\nMeadowbrook Stable, is stated to be\nthe \u201crealtor\u201d.\nCrofton wJI mane a tour of the\nNew York and Maryland tracks and\nalso take in the racing plants at\nChicagd and in Kentucky.\nThe Agua Caliente Jockey Club\nhas much to offer horsemen for its\nsecond Winter Meeting. There will\nbe sixteen stakes, as compared with\nnine offered at the inaugural meet\ning, the total added money value\nof which will be $170,000. The Agua\nCaliente Handicap will not only have\nSIOO,OOO added by the Jockey Club,\nbut it also carries with It a guaran\ntee that the winner will receive\nnot less than the same sum\u2014$ioo\n000.\nPOLITICAL\nAnnouncements\n7 t\nMrs Lucy Mitchell\nDemocratic Candidate\nfor\nCOUNTY RECORDER\nE. F. Bohlinger\nDemocratic Candidate\nfor\nREPRESENTATIVE j\n]SADDLES\nMADE TO ORDER\nNOGALES\nSADDLERY\nE. (Mike) Frankenpohl, Prop.\n313 MORLEY ATE.\nI\nGOOD NEWS TO SUFFERERS\nSCIATICA, LUMBAGO\nNEURALGIA GOUT\nMen and women, young and\nold, suffering from the most ex\ncruciating attacks of rheuma\ntism, having tried all that is j\nknown to medical science to find j\nrelief, have now been cured in\nmany remarkable ways with RU- j\nPROTEC. This new discovery is\nthe great Rheumatism remedy of\nthe century.\nWe guarantee that you will\nbe completely satisfied, relieved,\nand your rheumatism gone, or\nback goes your money. Price\nSI.OO a package.\nSOLD AT ALL DRUG STORES","height":"25185","width":"18114"}}
